Olaleye Aluko, Abuja The Nigerian Air Force on Wednesday unveiled two emergency ventilators which its personnel produced as parts of efforts to provide indigenous solutions to tackle the COVID-19 pandemic. The NAF, during a ceremony in Kaduna State, said the equipment was developed by a team of researchers from the Air Force Research and Development Centre; the Air Force Institute of Technology, Kaduna; in partnership with the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, Ahmadu Bello University in Zaria. The military said in a statement that the emergency ventilators, tagged “NAF E-Vents” would support the recovery of patients with respiratory diseases, including Acute Lung Injury and Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome, which were conditions arising from COVID-19. READ ALSO: FG can’t cope with increasing coronavirus cases – Minister The NAF said, “The E-Vents, which are intended for use when conventional invasive respiratory support resources have been exhausted, are found to deliver very satisfactory performance in air volume control and assist control modes and are now ready for human testing and further certification by relevant agencies. “Speaking during the unveiling ceremony, the Chief of the Air Staff, Air Marshal Sadique Abubakar, said the devastating effects of the COVID-19 required that ingenious and proactive steps be taken in order to protect lives and avert any form of national tragedy. “He noted that the NAF had continued to vigorously pursue a robust and result-oriented Research and Development policy with an emphasis on the provision of indigenous technological solutions.”